Morphi is a simple, powerful 3D design and modeling app for iPad, Mac + Windows. The app is used by a diverse community of people of all ages and skill levels in over 120 countries to create designs for AR+VR, 3D Printing, Animation, Game Design, Storytelling, Graphic Design and more .

There many things that make Morphi unique, including the following:

  • Draw 3D models in many ways, like sketching + basic drawing, symmetry, revolving lines, erasing lines, editing with control points + other 2D to 3D tools.
  • Robust 3D modeling tools including intersect, arrays and more.
  • Place, edit + view your 3D models in Augmented Reality which is built into iPad app (iPhone coming soon).
  • Image + video texture mapping tools for beautiful rendering of your 3D models.
  • Easy import + editing of STL files from other 3D modeling apps.
  • Simple 3D lithophanes/etchings.
  • Design anywhere including offline and with no logins.
  • Free trials on all platforms.

  • One-time price (free updates, no subscriptions) for individuals, schools, libraries, makerspaces, studios + offices: $4.99 per device for 20+ app purchases $9.99 per device for under 20 purchases

    Download the app for free on the App Store for iPad (https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/morphi/id833530351?mt=8) or on our website (http://www.morphiapp.com) for Mac and Windows.

bio: Hi !

Artists come to the Met every day to be inspired, discovering visual and technical solutions in works from every corner of the world, ranging from ancient times to the present day. They might attend a program, sketch from objects, or create their own copies of original paintings, as they have done since 1872 when the Met first allowed artists to re-create works of art on display.

The MediaLab at the Metropolitan Museum of Art has been working with Creative technologists and 3D enthusiasts, using photogrammetry and hand-held 3D scanners, to render objects in our collection into 3D models that we can share with the world. We encourage everyone to use our content, which represents the world's cultural heritage, to create their own creative works.

These scans aren't intended to be definitive, museum-quality models. These are scans for fun, for sharing, and to inspire creativity. Enjoy!

To learn more about the Met's MediaLab, and our Digital Media Department, check out :

  • our blog: http://www.metmuseum.org/about-the-museum/museum-departments/office-of-the-director/digital-media-department/digital-underground
  • our google+ community: https://plus.google.com/communities/102113316271410850848
  • and the NYC Museum MediaLab Meetup : http://www.meetup.com/NYC-Museum-MediaLab-Meetup/

I'm a keen model builder, maker or just generally creative person. I've always been creative and loved building models, with focus on working ones. When I got plastic display models as a kid I would always try to throw them hard enough to see if I could get any kind of aerodynamic behavior out of them, it obviously resulted in them always crashing instead.

I've always prioritized function over detail, mainly with RC airplanes with a focus on mimicking full scale structures using depron for large scale models. (Search Depron Airbus A340 on rcgroups).

So.. 3D printing. I've always been very bad with patients, maybe because I always have so many ideas so I hardly barely finish one before I start the other. 3D-printing has opened up a whole new world for me as a restless creative person as it removes the most time consuming part of the work, the actual building and reduce it to the more fun parts of planning and assembling.

The reason you see trains here is not because I love trains. I've never actually been interested in trains. But the combination of small kids, 3D-printing, a profession in electric motors and me getting really bored with playing with Brio trains with my son made this a perfect thing to do, make fun functional models that my son could play with and which presented just the right kind of challenge I look for.

Although flying things has always been my biggest passion, it was refreshing to make something non weight-critical for a change!

This means that you will most likely see a vast variety of things published here. My ideas range from everything from radio controlled planes, drones, boats to lamps, flowerpots, water bottle rocket accessories, art, musical instruments, electromechanics, robots and whatever else I can channel my need to be creative towards.

I'm not a pro CAD designer, my CAD skills are more driven by my ideas and projects. If I have an idea I will try as hard as I can to figure out how to accomplish it in Fusion 360 that I'm currently working in, always learning a lot along the way but probably not always doing it the most efficient way.

I am designing a Truly Awesome Strategy Board Game -
and I want YOUR miniature design! :D

But read on...

This 1900 steampunk world war strategy board game is about building and moving armies on a world map scale - standing out from tabletop/RPG games centered on single units on a tactical battlefield (often with amazing miniature artwork but not real strategy).
Here comes instead the grand old feeling of conquering the world!
Have you ever played Axis&Allies on the original map?
This is all the good stuff and more, with none of the annoying parts.

What I have:

  • An amazing modular world map, using multi-hex tiles to build the earth, as an approximated globe, with connecting edges - or any part, fantasy or random alternative world in any size, also allowing for completely custom game duration.
  • Great game mechanics, introducing innovative resource gathering, interactive neutral units, and parallel action phases: all players move and attack in the same turn - no more falling asleep while waiting for your fellows' turns!
  • Offering 3 levels of complexity, using basic or advanced units types for different strategic experiences; allowing allied or free-for-all games; several scenarios waiting to be implemented.
  • A non-clutter, no-frustration stacking device for game pieces and counters.

What I need for kickstarting this:

  • Awesome miniature prototypes !

I am looking for someone who would like to collaborate on this project, starting with a set of basic unit prototypes, in a sweet turn of century, WW1, steam and diesel punk design.

All feedback and advice is most welcome.
And thank you all for this awesome thingiverse!
Best regards

Small projects were working well (hence all of the cufflinks), but anything larger or delicate was failing horribly, with the extruder going on strike halfway through the process, leaving me with a half fininished sad hunk of plastic. 3DiTALY e’ un centro sviluppo progetti, dove chiunque può dare forma alle proprie idee, e dove qualunque progetto valido e interessante viene realizzato da un team di professionisti e può trovare un circuito alternativo e non convenzionale di distribuzione, basato su una rete di Store diffusi su tutto il territorio nazionale.
Nato come il primo 3D Printing Store ad operare in Italia, 3DiTALY oggi ha un vasto e variegato bacino di clientela: architetti, urbanisti, designers, makers, bricoleur, studenti, professionisti, ma anche importanti realtà produttive come Honda Italia, Trellenborg Pirelli, Samsung, Rai, Marina Militare Italiana.

La nostra mission oggi è rivalutare il design e l’artigianato italiano, due settori che hanno reso da sempre famoso il nostro Paese a livello internazionale. 3Ditaly attualmente è un luogo d'incontro e di scambio, dove si svolgono attività come service di stampa, modellazione CAD, workshop formativi, vendita di stampanti, scanner 3D, schede Arduino, materiali per la stampa, oggetti di design. In un 3DiTALY Store si fa ricerca e sperimentazione continua, da un lato con i clienti, dall'altro con i produttori di tecnologie.

3DiTALY come concept nasce dalla cultura del Do It Yourself (DIY). Grazie a tecnologie come le stampanti 3d ognuno di noi può essere un maker, scavalcando i tradizionali modelli di produzione, distribuzione delle merci e consumo. Il nostro claim parla chiaro: “Se lo puoi immaginare lo puoi creare”. Questo per noi significa seguire step-by-step tutti i progetti dei nostri clienti e trasformare così le idee di chi si rivolge a noi in realtà concrete. Personalizzazione assoluta e unicità del prodotto sono le nostre parole chiave. Portiamo avanti progetti flessibili, evitando costose e standardizzate produzioni in serie. Il mondo maker è libero e aperto a tutti grazie a programmi open source gratuiti e facili da utilizzare. E’ l’internet delle cose dove l’atomo è il nuovo bit.

bio:
I am a software developer by trade, an apprenticed carpenter and jeweler by family tradition, and an artist by insatiable urge to create. I am pretty new to 3D printing, having just branched into it through access to a local Makerspace. My first experiment in 3D printing was producing a trumpet mouthpiece for easy modification and addition to my Suzuki Melodion. I wanted to try to use a trumpet mouthpiece on the instrument, but didn't want to machine down an expensive brass one to find it wasn't to my playing taste. The 3D printed mouthpiece was a perfect prototype, and I enjoyed producing it so much that I decided to learn more about 3D printing.

I now design, print, and paint tabletop gaming miniatures as a hobby. I have always enjoyed painting miniatures, and am happy to be able to print my own and even throw together new ones from scratch when I am looking for something very specific.
